In addition to the diary study, four care coordinators and between two and four team managers were selected for interview from each of the 12 sites. Team managers were asked to identify care coordinators who had very little, or a great deal, of experience with IBs, to compare and contrast their views. Interviews were carried out with care coordinators from teams working with the full range of adult social care service users (people with learning disabilities, older people (including those with mental health problems), younger physically disabled people, and users of adult [i.e. not old age] mental health services). These semi-structured interviews complemented the diary study by enabling a more detailed investigation of how IBs affected care coordinator time use, and interviews therefore included:


Experiences of implementation;

Accounts of, and opinions about, the new processes of assessment, resource allocation, support planning and review;

Changes to care coordinators’ roles;

Identification of barriers and facilitating factors in implementation;

Apparent benefits and drawbacks of IBs;

Perceptions of the impact of IBs on social work practice.
Altogether 48 care coordinators (including one local authority-employed broker) and 43 team managers were interviewed. The interviews with care coordinators were conducted face-to-face and those with team managers by telephone. All interviews were audio recorded with the consent of the participant and fully transcribed for analysis. A thematic coding frame was developed, using NVIVO 7, guided initially by the interview schedule but latterly substantially informed by the data. Transcripts were fully coded, data saturation being reached towards the end of the process, that is, no further codes were being generated.
